WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.700 --> 00:00:04.440
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Good afternoon and welcome.

00:00:04.440 --> 00:00:08.280
It's an honor and a privilege for me today
to introduce one of the world's greatest contemporary

00:00:08.280 --> 00:00:12.920
artists and Seattle native son, Dale Chihuly.

00:00:12.920 --> 00:00:18.390
Dale has popularized and revolutionized the
Studio Glass Movement, bringing this new American

00:00:18.390 --> 00:00:21.370
art to international fame.

00:00:21.370 --> 00:00:25.910
His work is included in more than 200 major
museum collections, which has to be pretty

00:00:25.910 --> 00:00:32.410
close to setting the record for number of
installations for a living artist as he's

00:00:32.410 --> 00:00:37.170
exhibited in numerous prestigious museums
and galleries all over the world, such as

00:00:37.170 --> 00:00:43.420
the Victoria and Albert Museum in London and
other exhibitions, including Chihuly in the

00:00:43.420 --> 00:00:47.850
Light of Jerusalem, which broke a record for
a million visitors.

00:00:47.850 --> 00:00:50.560
He's also well-known for his garden installations.

00:00:50.560 --> 00:00:55.310
He studied here at University of Washington,
the University of Wisconsin-Madison, and Rhode

00:00:55.310 --> 00:00:56.500
Island School of Design.

00:00:56.500 --> 00:01:00.661
And he's been the recipient of many awards,
including eleven honorary doctorates and two

00:01:00.661 --> 00:01:03.450
fellowships for the National Endowment of
the Arts.

00:01:03.450 --> 00:01:07.920
Dale and his team, working in a boathouse
by the water here in Seattle, continue to

00:01:07.920 --> 00:01:11.340
push the limits of glassblowing craftsmanship
and glass art.

00:01:11.340 --> 00:01:15.999
And I have to say, it was seven years ago
I was lucky enough to get to visit the boathouse

00:01:15.999 --> 00:01:17.950
here in Seattle.

00:01:17.950 --> 00:01:19.030
And I was there with my mother.

00:01:19.030 --> 00:01:23.409
And as we left, I think we drove about five
blocks without saying anything.

00:01:23.409 --> 00:01:28.289
And then, my mother stopped and said, "That
is the closest experience anyone will ever

00:01:28.289 --> 00:01:33.520
have to being at Giverny with Monet when he
was painting the water lilies."

00:01:33.520 --> 00:01:39.639
[laughs] She said it was just amazing to be
with an artist of that caliber and quality

00:01:39.639 --> 00:01:43.930
and inspiration while he's doing some of the
best work of his career.

00:01:43.930 --> 00:01:49.310
And the most amazing part of all of this is
that Dale is opening his own garden here in

00:01:49.310 --> 00:01:50.560
Seattle next month.

00:01:50.560 --> 00:01:53.509
And he's gonna give us an overview of that
exhibit.

00:01:53.509 --> 00:01:55.490
It's Chihuly Garden and Glass.

00:01:55.490 --> 00:02:00.609
And after that, we'll also be joined by his
wife, Leslie Chihuly, and Michelle Bufano

00:02:00.609 --> 00:02:01.889
for some questions.

00:02:01.889 --> 00:02:07.130
And with that, Dale Chihuly.

00:02:07.130 --> 00:02:08.179
[applause]

00:02:08.179 --> 00:02:12.200
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: Thank you.

00:02:12.200 --> 00:02:17.670
Leslie and I are happy to be here and we're
going to give you a little sneak preview of

00:02:17.670 --> 00:02:20.879
Chihuly Garden and Glass.

00:02:20.879 --> 00:02:27.760
I'm gonna start with a seven-minute video
that will give you a history of my work.

00:02:27.760 --> 00:02:30.420
So, if we could queue that up.

00:02:30.420 --> 00:02:31.420
[pause]

00:02:31.420 --> 00:02:32.420
[plays video]

00:02:32.420 --> 00:02:37.870
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: I've often been asked what
would I like to do that I haven't done.

00:02:37.870 --> 00:02:43.510
And the first thing that comes to mind is
that I'd like to build a conservatory or a

00:02:43.510 --> 00:02:48.370
glass house and to design everything that
goes inside it.

00:02:48.370 --> 00:02:54.960
[upbeat music with drum and guitar]

00:02:54.960 --> 00:03:00.010
I think ideas come a great deal from being
alone.

00:03:00.010 --> 00:03:04.739
And even though I work with a great team of
people all day long, I happen to be an early

00:03:04.739 --> 00:03:05.739
riser.

00:03:05.739 --> 00:03:13.030
So, I'm often up at four, five in the morning
and have several hours to be on my own and

00:03:13.030 --> 00:03:14.209
think about things.

00:03:14.209 --> 00:03:19.170
There's just all sorts of possibilities with
glass.

00:03:19.170 --> 00:03:22.799
I can't think of too many materials that haven't
been exploited except for glass.

00:03:22.799 --> 00:03:26.739
One night I melted some stained glass 'cause
I had this little kiln 'cause I was fusing

00:03:26.739 --> 00:03:27.840
the glass together.

00:03:27.840 --> 00:03:34.749
I put in a piece of iron pipe that I probably
bought at the hardware store, and blew a bubble.

00:03:34.749 --> 00:03:37.550
I had never seen glass blowing before.

00:03:37.550 --> 00:03:39.400
Like there was a picture on the wall.

00:03:39.400 --> 00:03:45.430
I remember the picture clearly of a glassblower
with his cheeks all puffed out, like he was

00:03:45.430 --> 00:03:46.430
blowing a trumpet.

00:03:46.430 --> 00:03:49.080
So, from that point on, I wanted to be a glassblower.

00:03:49.080 --> 00:03:51.700
[drum beats]

00:03:51.700 --> 00:03:57.810
In 1971, myself and some friends started Pilchuck
Glass School.

00:03:57.810 --> 00:04:03.659
Pilchuck Glass School really is what established
Seattle as the preeminent glass center of

00:04:03.659 --> 00:04:05.510
the world--not just Seattle.

00:04:05.510 --> 00:04:09.569
This is spread out into much of the Northwest.

00:04:09.569 --> 00:04:15.290
And every summer, we went back to Pilchuck,
which was an experimental glass workshop.

00:04:15.290 --> 00:04:19.750
It was kind of a school, but more than, I
would say more than anything, it was a place

00:04:19.750 --> 00:04:26.100
where we developed ideas and experimented,
back when we didn't really care about sales

00:04:26.100 --> 00:04:27.410
or anything like that.

00:04:27.410 --> 00:04:33.260
So, nothing held us back from doing a lot
of experimentation.

00:04:33.260 --> 00:04:37.950
The whole idea of making art, as far as I'm
concerned, it comes from just doing it over

00:04:37.950 --> 00:04:38.960
and over and over.

00:04:38.960 --> 00:04:41.100
We just have to be making a lot of mistakes.

00:04:41.100 --> 00:04:45.000
And finally, you've just done so many thousands
of pieces that it becomes sort of natural

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:52.410
but you gotta go through five or ten years
of making mistakes all the time before you

00:04:52.410 --> 00:04:53.410
can develop that.

00:04:53.410 --> 00:04:54.410
[hissing]

00:04:54.410 --> 00:04:55.420
Don't worry about the form quite so much.

00:04:55.420 --> 00:05:00.660
Worry about the speed and worry about the
ease of the operation.

00:05:00.660 --> 00:05:04.170
Once you get all of that going, then everything,
the form comes.

00:05:04.170 --> 00:05:05.170
You got it down now.

00:05:05.170 --> 00:05:06.170
Let's get it down.

00:05:06.170 --> 00:05:10.680
Once we get it down, let's keep it there and
roll it.

00:05:10.680 --> 00:05:11.680
Nice.

00:05:11.680 --> 00:05:13.800
Over and over and over and over.

00:05:13.800 --> 00:05:17.160
And then those forms will get better and better
and better.

00:05:17.160 --> 00:05:19.970
I've been working with glass now for 40 years.

00:05:19.970 --> 00:05:23.530
And, of course, the work started small.

00:05:23.530 --> 00:05:26.350
And it got larger and larger.

00:05:26.350 --> 00:05:30.180
And then, at a certain point, the pieces were
just big enough.

00:05:30.180 --> 00:05:33.700
They became hard to handle if they were any
bigger.

00:05:33.700 --> 00:05:38.100
And around that same time, I started architectural
installations.

00:05:38.100 --> 00:05:41.730
I have a degree in interior design and architecture.

00:05:41.730 --> 00:05:45.710
And so, that was very comfortable working
in the spaces.

00:05:45.710 --> 00:05:52.580
Even my smaller objects often had--I think
of them as architectural because they'll have

00:05:52.580 --> 00:05:53.970
one part inside another.

00:05:53.970 --> 00:05:56.910
It was a very smooth transition to--.

00:05:56.910 --> 00:05:58.780
The installation started small.

00:05:58.780 --> 00:06:04.400
And then, as we learned how to put things
together, we quit making the parts big and

00:06:04.400 --> 00:06:06.400
we went back to making the parts small.

00:06:06.400 --> 00:06:09.750
And so, it's massing all that color together.

00:06:09.750 --> 00:06:14.240
When you look at the sun, and there's a thousand
or more parts in it, there's that much yellow

00:06:14.240 --> 00:06:18.620
and the sun is coming through it.

00:06:18.620 --> 00:06:20.411
No artificial light is going through it.

00:06:20.411 --> 00:06:28.500
It just, it's just a massive amount of yellow
color and it's in this big, simple form.

00:06:28.500 --> 00:06:33.030
It just has a lot of power when you see it
in that way.

00:06:33.030 --> 00:06:41.500
So, it was a natural thing for me to go from
the smaller works to the larger works.

00:06:41.500 --> 00:06:43.270
[jazzy music]

00:06:43.270 --> 00:06:48.770
I couldn't do one-tenth of what I'm doing
if I didn't have a big team.

00:06:48.770 --> 00:06:53.530
So, the complexity of the big shows takes
a great deal of people.

00:06:53.530 --> 00:06:58.660
And I've been very fortunate to, over the
years, build that team.

00:06:58.660 --> 00:07:02.870
Maybe I got a little bit of that organizational
ability from my dad, the butcher that was

00:07:02.870 --> 00:07:03.870
a union organizer.

00:07:03.870 --> 00:07:04.870
I don't know what.

00:07:04.870 --> 00:07:11.840
But I got very fortunate in being able to
work with great people.

00:07:11.840 --> 00:07:17.720
[Spanish music]

00:07:17.720 --> 00:07:21.910
I woke up one morning and said that I wanted
to hang chandeliers over the canals of Venice.

00:07:21.910 --> 00:07:27.130
And then, from that came the concept of working
in different countries--making chandeliers

00:07:27.130 --> 00:07:30.010
and taking them to Venice.

00:07:30.010 --> 00:07:31.510
The first country was Finland.

00:07:31.510 --> 00:07:33.830
The second was Ireland.

00:07:33.830 --> 00:07:36.140
The third was Mexico.

00:07:36.140 --> 00:07:37.290
[Spanish music]

00:07:37.290 --> 00:07:42.610
It gave me an opportunity to build the chandeliers
or make installations.

00:07:42.610 --> 00:07:46.720
And then, right outside, there were woods
or rivers to work in.

00:07:46.720 --> 00:07:47.720
[splash]

00:07:47.720 --> 00:07:53.980
And I always worked outside to some degree,
but since 1995, it's become a more important

00:07:53.980 --> 00:07:55.850
part of my work.

00:07:55.850 --> 00:07:56.850
[splash]

00:07:56.850 --> 00:07:57.850
Three.

00:07:57.850 --> 00:07:58.850
Three.

00:07:58.850 --> 00:07:59.850
[splash]

00:07:59.850 --> 00:08:06.920
You take that idea, make the decision to go
with it and go down that road and see what

00:08:06.920 --> 00:08:08.080
happens.

00:08:08.080 --> 00:08:09.080
And sometimes, it doesn't work.

00:08:09.080 --> 00:08:14.060
Most of the time, I've been fortunate that
a lot of the projects have worked or ideas

00:08:14.060 --> 00:08:26.940
have worked.

00:08:26.940 --> 00:08:39.810
[Spanish music]

00:08:39.810 --> 00:09:09.650
&gt;&gt;Jeffrey Wright: My family and I have been
admirers of Dale and his work for many years.

00:09:09.650 --> 00:09:15.440
And his art has been symbolizing to visitors--the
creativity and the inspiration that lives

00:09:15.440 --> 00:09:17.990
and breathes in our city.

00:09:17.990 --> 00:09:22.760
Dale has designed something truly beautiful
and inspiring for our community and the world.

00:09:22.760 --> 00:09:27.440
And personally, I can't wait to see the finished
product.

00:09:27.440 --> 00:09:33.280
[classical music]

00:09:33.280 --> 00:09:43.630
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: So, thanks again for coming.

00:09:43.630 --> 00:09:47.710
See you here next spring.

00:09:47.710 --> 00:09:48.710
[applause]

00:09:48.710 --> 00:09:50.550
[end video]

00:09:50.550 --> 00:09:54.840
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: I guess it's springtime.

00:09:54.840 --> 00:10:00.840
We're gonna open in 29 days, I think it is.

00:10:00.840 --> 00:10:04.630
May 21st.

00:10:04.630 --> 00:10:14.680
Right next to the Space Needle is about 100
feet over here and it's gonna be this long

00:10:14.680 --> 00:10:17.410
building that's called the Exhibition Hall.

00:10:17.410 --> 00:10:27.320
And that will have nine rooms inside the hall.

00:10:27.320 --> 00:10:30.660
This is the glass house.

00:10:30.660 --> 00:10:33.020
This is the garden.

00:10:33.020 --> 00:10:35.060
[pause]

00:10:35.060 --> 00:10:40.680
I'll go through a couple of the rooms with
you.

00:10:40.680 --> 00:10:50.580
This is an installation I did in 1971 for
a museum in Switzerland.

00:10:50.580 --> 00:10:57.890
And it's one of the first large-scale exhibition
that's about 30 feet across.

00:10:57.890 --> 00:11:06.290
And I've always loved this piece, so I decided
to do it over for the project.

00:11:06.290 --> 00:11:14.400
The next slide is the Northwest Indian room,
which is a take-off from a room that I have

00:11:14.400 --> 00:11:20.870
in my studio in the boathouse in Seattle,
showing Pendleton Blankets, Northwest Coast

00:11:20.870 --> 00:11:31.110
Indian baskets, Edward Curtis prints on the
wall that you can't see, and some of my glass

00:11:31.110 --> 00:11:36.200
work that's influenced by the Indian baskets.

00:11:36.200 --> 00:11:38.070
[pause]

00:11:38.070 --> 00:11:46.210
The Glasshouse, by the way, we started this
project last August.

00:11:46.210 --> 00:11:48.160
So, it's just gonna be--.

00:11:48.160 --> 00:11:53.320
It'll take nine months from start to finish
on the project.

00:11:53.320 --> 00:11:56.740
And the Glasshouse is just about finished.

00:11:56.740 --> 00:12:00.280
You can see part of the piece that's gonna
be inside there.

00:12:00.280 --> 00:12:09.630
It's the piece will be a hundred feet long
and 25 feet high inside the Glasshouse.

00:12:09.630 --> 00:12:11.930
And then, you come out of the Glasshouse.

00:12:11.930 --> 00:12:15.089
We went by the Temple of the Sun.

00:12:15.089 --> 00:12:19.120
Over here is an installation of blue pieces.

00:12:19.120 --> 00:12:21.120
[pause]

00:12:21.120 --> 00:12:29.160
Now, we're gonna go to the Collection Café
where there's 28 different collections shown

00:12:29.160 --> 00:12:30.500
in the Café.

00:12:30.500 --> 00:12:36.740
There'll be 23 tables, each table having a
sheet of glass on top.

00:12:36.740 --> 00:12:40.640
And you look down through it into a collection.

00:12:40.640 --> 00:12:41.640
[pause]

00:12:41.640 --> 00:12:51.500
Now, I'm gonna bring up my lovely wife, Leslie,
to talk to you about the partnering we're

00:12:51.500 --> 00:12:56.480
doing with other institutions around the project.

00:12:56.480 --> 00:12:57.670
[applause]

00:12:57.670 --> 00:13:02.420
&gt;&gt;Leslie Chihuly: Got reverb?

00:13:02.420 --> 00:13:07.170
It is all OK?

00:13:07.170 --> 00:13:12.630
I hear a little something there.

00:13:12.630 --> 00:13:15.470
It'll settle down.

00:13:15.470 --> 00:13:19.070
I just wanna thank Google for inviting us
here today.

00:13:19.070 --> 00:13:25.360
And I wanna thank you for the extraordinary
work that you're doing in featuring and championing

00:13:25.360 --> 00:13:30.120
artists and creative thinkers by having talks
like this.

00:13:30.120 --> 00:13:34.600
I know Dale did one before and we're just
very honored to be invited back.

00:13:34.600 --> 00:13:37.820
So, thank you all for having us on the campus
today.

00:13:37.820 --> 00:13:39.220
I'm Leslie Chihuly.

00:13:39.220 --> 00:13:42.649
I'm president of Chihuly Studio and Portland
Press.

00:13:42.649 --> 00:13:46.840
I'm also the Board Chair of the Seattle Symphony
Orchestra.

00:13:46.840 --> 00:13:52.120
And like many of you, Dale and I are very
proud of the city we live in.

00:13:52.120 --> 00:13:56.130
We wanna make a difference and we think that
this is really one of the great cities on

00:13:56.130 --> 00:13:57.150
the planet.

00:13:57.150 --> 00:14:02.089
It's a very special place in that it's big
enough to have a rich and diverse cultural

00:14:02.089 --> 00:14:05.830
scene, and small enough where people feel
they can make a difference.

00:14:05.830 --> 00:14:07.900
We're starters and builders.

00:14:07.900 --> 00:14:13.170
Many of us in Seattle are newcomers drawn
by spectacular nature and beauty and kept

00:14:13.170 --> 00:14:18.660
here by work, careers, families, and the opportunity
to participate in meaningful ways in the life

00:14:18.660 --> 00:14:19.660
of the city.

00:14:19.660 --> 00:14:25.860
With vision, talent, capital combined with
philanthropy and volunteerism, we have created

00:14:25.860 --> 00:14:31.350
a community that attracts some of the best
and the brightest in the arts and technology,

00:14:31.350 --> 00:14:34.250
medicine, business, and entrepreneurism.

00:14:34.250 --> 00:14:39.290
We're celebrating the 50th Anniversary of
the World's Fair, where the builders and thinkers

00:14:39.290 --> 00:14:44.830
of that time pointed to a bright future, full
of possibility, innovation, exploration, and

00:14:44.830 --> 00:14:45.830
achievement.

00:14:45.830 --> 00:14:52.920
In the last 50 years, Seattle has built the
cultural organizations we enjoy today.

00:14:52.920 --> 00:14:59.210
Imagine Seattle and Tacoma without McCaw Hall,
Benaroya Hall, the restored Paramount, the

00:14:59.210 --> 00:15:04.920
expanded Seattle Art Museum and the sculpture
park, the Tacoma Art Museum, Museum of Glass,

00:15:04.920 --> 00:15:11.500
the Northwest African American Museum, the
Intiman, the Rep, the ACT--so many other museums,

00:15:11.500 --> 00:15:18.149
galleries, and diverse organizations of all
sizes doing film, dance, music, and theater.

00:15:18.149 --> 00:15:21.800
But another important anniversary is happening
right now, which you may not know of, which

00:15:21.800 --> 00:15:26.580
is called the 50th Anniversary of the Studio
Glass Movement in this country.

00:15:26.580 --> 00:15:31.680
A two thousand year old technology was about
to be turned upside-down and inside-out by

00:15:31.680 --> 00:15:36.720
a small group of artists who began to experiment
with the natural qualities of hot glass.

00:15:36.720 --> 00:15:40.980
They began to push the material beyond anything
that had ever been seen or done historically.

00:15:40.980 --> 00:15:46.930
Testing and failing, being willing to try
over and over again to achieve new scale,

00:15:46.930 --> 00:15:51.990
to use old techniques in new ways, gave birth
to a new movement and a new period in art

00:15:51.990 --> 00:15:53.110
history.

00:15:53.110 --> 00:15:57.209
We also celebrated the 40th Anniversary of
Pilchuck Glass School this past year.

00:15:57.209 --> 00:15:59.089
It was co-founded by Dale.

00:15:59.089 --> 00:16:03.529
And the school was built out of the dreams
of a few artists combined with the generosity

00:16:03.529 --> 00:16:08.709
of philanthropists Annie and John Hauberg,
who decided to contribute lands and funds

00:16:08.709 --> 00:16:13.060
to some young people who had ideas, energy,
and passion to create.

00:16:13.060 --> 00:16:16.790
We're so proud that that school is going to
be one of the founding partners of Chihuly

00:16:16.790 --> 00:16:18.850
Garden and Glass.

00:16:18.850 --> 00:16:24.290
What you will see when you visit Chihuly Garden
and Glass is the work of a lifetime by a Northwest

00:16:24.290 --> 00:16:25.290
artist.

00:16:25.290 --> 00:16:31.550
It encompasses the education, the mentoring,
the influences, inspiration, travels and experience

00:16:31.550 --> 00:16:35.830
of a lifetime spent looking at the world through
an artist's sensibility.

00:16:35.830 --> 00:16:39.500
When the Wright family, owners of the Space
Needle, invited Dale as an artist to look

00:16:39.500 --> 00:16:44.910
at the old Fun Forest site, they invited me
and our organization, Chihuly Studio, to participate

00:16:44.910 --> 00:16:46.259
in the process.

00:16:46.259 --> 00:16:50.500
We needed to make a case to the community
about how private use of public land would

00:16:50.500 --> 00:16:53.750
be a benefit to the community as a whole.

00:16:53.750 --> 00:16:59.040
Person by person, group by group, at City
Hall, in private and public gathering places,

00:16:59.040 --> 00:17:04.150
we began to speak to the importance of this
project for kids, for fellow artists, for

00:17:04.150 --> 00:17:09.499
tourists, for families, for the city, and
for the Seattle Center as a place where everyone

00:17:09.499 --> 00:17:13.289
could come and see what is possible when you
have a commitment to making the world a more

00:17:13.289 --> 00:17:16.049
beautiful and aesthetic place.

00:17:16.049 --> 00:17:21.509
It says something about our city that we can
recognize how one person's success as an artist

00:17:21.509 --> 00:17:26.149
means that others can have that same opportunity
to imagine new worlds and to see them take

00:17:26.149 --> 00:17:28.199
shape in a lifetime.

00:17:28.199 --> 00:17:31.570
We need to continuously support our arts.

00:17:31.570 --> 00:17:37.929
We hope this project will provide more visibility
and success, not only to our founding non-profit

00:17:37.929 --> 00:17:43.200
partners, which include Pratt Fine Arts Center,
Pilchuck Glass School, ArtsFund an the Seattle

00:17:43.200 --> 00:17:48.739
Public Schools, but to all of the arts organizations
in the community who exist to serve the educational,

00:17:48.739 --> 00:17:51.710
civic, and cultural needs of our city.

00:17:51.710 --> 00:17:55.990
We hope that it is a window into the very
creative life of our city and that it is a

00:17:55.990 --> 00:18:01.210
gathering place where more discussion and
more advocacy for what we value can happen.

00:18:01.210 --> 00:18:05.239
Most of our arts organizations don't have
the endowments of older institutions around

00:18:05.239 --> 00:18:06.239
the rest of the country.

00:18:06.239 --> 00:18:10.850
So, our next push will be to endow the cultural
institutions we value so that we can sustain

00:18:10.850 --> 00:18:13.059
them for the next generations.

00:18:13.059 --> 00:18:17.320
Dale and I believe that exposure to the arts
should be a part of everyone's educational

00:18:17.320 --> 00:18:21.419
experience, which is why we're excited about
Chihuly Garden and Glass and partnership that

00:18:21.419 --> 00:18:23.660
it will have with the Seattle Public Schools.

00:18:23.660 --> 00:18:28.769
A science curriculum is being developed for
all eighth graders in the Seattle area.

00:18:28.769 --> 00:18:34.100
We believe that the understanding of creativity
within one's self and seeing it in others

00:18:34.100 --> 00:18:38.869
helps to build community and translates into
more fulfilling and productive lives.

00:18:38.869 --> 00:18:42.690
So, we need to continue to make the case for
arts in our community.

00:18:42.690 --> 00:18:44.169
We don't take it for granted.

00:18:44.169 --> 00:18:47.860
And we remember that is it our arts that give
the city its pulse.

00:18:47.860 --> 00:18:51.700
With the help and thinking of the many creative,
innovative, and entrepreneurial members of

00:18:51.700 --> 00:18:57.249
our community, many of whom are in this room
today and in the virtual room we're experiencing,

00:18:57.249 --> 00:19:00.739
I imagine that we can be the leaders for the
rest of the world in terms of how to use our

00:19:00.739 --> 00:19:05.809
existing public and private resources wisely
and to leverage those resources to a sustainable

00:19:05.809 --> 00:19:06.860
future.

00:19:06.860 --> 00:19:10.809
We hope Chihuly Garden and Glass will be a
source of joy and inspiration for everyone

00:19:10.809 --> 00:19:15.149
in our city and that people who come to visit
from other cities and other countries around

00:19:15.149 --> 00:19:19.960
the world will see that Seattle is a place
that supports its artists, its businesses,

00:19:19.960 --> 00:19:22.580
and can dream big dreams and make them happen.

00:19:22.580 --> 00:19:27.309
We invite everyone to go out and participate
in all kinds of arts experiences in the community--music,

00:19:27.309 --> 00:19:30.429
screenings of theater, film, dance, and poetry.

00:19:30.429 --> 00:19:35.039
And we see that the beauty of creativity is
that it enjoys many languages.

00:19:35.039 --> 00:19:38.330
And the more people are exposed, the more
they can make connections and lead creative

00:19:38.330 --> 00:19:40.279
lives in all fields of endeavor.

00:19:40.279 --> 00:19:42.019
So, thank you so much for having us.

00:19:42.019 --> 00:19:46.490
I wanna also introduce you today to Michelle
Bufano, who's the executive director of Chihuly

00:19:46.490 --> 00:19:47.490
Garden and Glass.

