00:25:19.049 --> 00:25:23.399
But tell us a little bit about your connection
to Seattle.

00:25:23.399 --> 00:25:25.309
It's, you're almost synonymous with it.

00:25:25.309 --> 00:25:27.529
I think each of you has your own special connection.

00:25:27.529 --> 00:25:32.940
And I'd like to hear a little bit about, I
think this exhibit is really a celebration

00:25:32.940 --> 00:25:34.220
of Seattle, itself.

00:25:34.220 --> 00:25:38.200
And so, maybe you can talk a little bit about
your relationship with the city.

00:25:38.200 --> 00:25:39.200
[pause]

00:25:39.200 --> 00:25:44.600
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: Well, I went to college in
Tacoma for the first year.

00:25:44.600 --> 00:25:45.769
I didn't wanna go to school.

00:25:45.769 --> 00:25:47.529
I was not a very good student.

00:25:47.529 --> 00:25:51.859
My mother talked me into going to school.

00:25:51.859 --> 00:25:57.619
And that winter, I decorated her basement
and thought I could be a great interior designer.

00:25:57.619 --> 00:26:04.720
So, I transferred to the University of Washington
in Seattle.

00:26:04.720 --> 00:26:09.749
And I got a degree in Interior Design and
Architecture.

00:26:09.749 --> 00:26:19.580
And it was during that time that I was beginning
to work with glass and weaving and tapestries.

00:26:19.580 --> 00:26:23.999
And one night, I melted some glass and blew
a bubble.

00:26:23.999 --> 00:26:27.880
And from that point on, I wanted to be a glassblower.

00:26:27.880 --> 00:26:34.989
And I went to Alaska and became a commercial
fisherman to save money to go to graduate

00:26:34.989 --> 00:26:38.970
school at the University of Wisconsin.

00:26:38.970 --> 00:26:42.299
And I went to Venice, Italy after that.

00:26:42.299 --> 00:26:48.019
And I then went to the Rhode Island School
of Design to start a glass department there,

00:26:48.019 --> 00:26:50.999
but at the same time, we started the Pilchuck
Glass School.

00:26:50.999 --> 00:26:56.899
So, every summer, I would come back to Seattle
to Pilchuck and every winter, I would stay

00:26:56.899 --> 00:26:58.039
in Rhode Island.

00:26:58.039 --> 00:27:00.409
And I did that for ten years.

00:27:00.409 --> 00:27:08.679
And when my sales of my glass matched my income
as a professor, which was 18 thousand dollars

00:27:08.679 --> 00:27:17.289
a year in 1980, I quit teaching and came back
to Seattle and have been here ever since.

00:27:17.289 --> 00:27:20.950
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: And Leslie, I know you've
been working with numerous partners, some

00:27:20.950 --> 00:27:22.970
of whom are, most of them are based here in
Seattle.

00:27:22.970 --> 00:27:25.580
Maybe you can talk a little bit about your
connection to the city.

00:27:25.580 --> 00:27:26.580
&gt;&gt;Leslie Chihuly: Sure.

00:27:26.580 --> 00:27:30.830
Well, I moved here in '85 and went to graduate
school at U Dub in Russian Studies.

00:27:30.830 --> 00:27:34.590
And at that time, you couldn't find a restaurant
that was open past nine.

00:27:34.590 --> 00:27:35.590
We didn't have--.

00:27:35.590 --> 00:27:38.840
I mentioned a lot of the halls and the things
that have happened really that have been built

00:27:38.840 --> 00:27:39.840
since I moved here.

00:27:39.840 --> 00:27:44.679
And I think what I saw was a city with a future,
the fact I didn't even think it really was

00:27:44.679 --> 00:27:45.679
a city.

00:27:45.679 --> 00:27:46.679
I thought it was a town.

00:27:46.679 --> 00:27:48.909
And I think it's become a city in this period
of time.

00:27:48.909 --> 00:27:54.320
And so, it's a really exuberant and hopeful
place in terms of being able to build and

00:27:54.320 --> 00:27:55.490
do new things.

00:27:55.490 --> 00:27:59.690
We're not burdened with a lot of the traditions
and history of older cities.

00:27:59.690 --> 00:28:02.889
And so, it's a city where everything is possible.

00:28:02.889 --> 00:28:08.609
What's exciting to me about this project in
the context of Seattle is not only the aesthetics

00:28:08.609 --> 00:28:13.389
and the fact that we're celebrating a local
artist, as it were, but that we're going to

00:28:13.389 --> 00:28:17.659
be a convening place for all of the arts and
for certainly the community partners.

00:28:17.659 --> 00:28:19.429
And we hope that list will grow over time.

00:28:19.429 --> 00:28:22.919
And I'm working with Michelle and many of
us are working hard to think about how the

00:28:22.919 --> 00:28:27.590
space will be used over time to really bring
more attention to the incredible arts that

00:28:27.590 --> 00:28:28.809
we enjoy in the city.

00:28:28.809 --> 00:28:32.690
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: And Michelle, you're now
the Executive Director of this exhibit that

00:28:32.690 --> 00:28:37.739
