on the campus--on the Seattle Center campus.

00:28:52.309 --> 00:28:55.059
And it's really exciting right now because
of the 50th.

00:28:55.059 --> 00:28:57.090
There's so much going on.

00:28:57.090 --> 00:29:00.080
King Tut is opening in a month as well.

00:29:00.080 --> 00:29:02.390
We have the symphony, the ballet.

00:29:02.390 --> 00:29:05.460
But it's really becoming a focal point, the
whole campus.

00:29:05.460 --> 00:29:11.039
And this project is spearheading a program
called "Center Nights," where people will,

00:29:11.039 --> 00:29:17.240
everyone who's on campus will develop programming
and we'll open up our doors to great programming,

00:29:17.240 --> 00:29:19.640
at least once a quarter for people to come.

00:29:19.640 --> 00:29:25.840
So, I see it as really an opportunity to build
excitement and to bring people to one center

00:29:25.840 --> 00:29:27.090
place for the arts.

00:29:27.090 --> 00:29:29.610
So, that's been an exciting part of it.

00:29:29.610 --> 00:29:36.359
Personally, I've been involved with Dale's
work since I worked at the Tacoma Art Museum

00:29:36.359 --> 00:29:38.710
and then opened the Museum of Glass.

00:29:38.710 --> 00:29:44.549
So, I've been a big fan of glass and most
recently came for Pratt Fine Arts Center,

00:29:44.549 --> 00:29:48.009
which is one of the community partners for
this project.

00:29:48.009 --> 00:29:52.750
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: One of the interesting
things of the museum is there's a café.

00:29:52.750 --> 00:29:55.580
And it's called Collections Café.

00:29:55.580 --> 00:30:00.220
And I think that one of the things that really
surprised me when I got to visit the boathouse

00:30:00.220 --> 00:30:07.389
was all the different collections that you
have, Dale--everything from shaving brushes

00:30:07.389 --> 00:30:13.779
to accordions to Navajo blankets to something
I didn't even realize existed, but there were

00:30:13.779 --> 00:30:18.210
string dispensers, which looked like little
faces on the wall with pieces of string coming

00:30:18.210 --> 00:30:22.570
out of their mouths because before there were
tape dispensers, there were string dispensers.

00:30:22.570 --> 00:30:27.279
And I know that collecting and just collecting
lots of different objects and looking at all

00:30:27.279 --> 00:30:30.519
the differences is a big part of your process
as an artist.

00:30:30.519 --> 00:30:33.539
So, tell us what some of the collections that
you're more proud of.

00:30:33.539 --> 00:30:36.879
Maybe you want to give us a little bit of
background of the café and what people can

00:30:36.879 --> 00:30:38.049
see there.

00:30:38.049 --> 00:30:44.000
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: Well, I mean, I started when
I was a kid.

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:53.659
But I think a lot of kids collect things--marbles
or toy soldiers or beach glass.

00:30:53.659 --> 00:30:55.460
But I just kept collecting.

00:30:55.460 --> 00:30:58.409
Usually, you stop at a certain age.

00:30:58.409 --> 00:31:00.889
And I've always collected.

00:31:00.889 --> 00:31:12.159
Like, I have 500 accordions and 800 Pendleton
blankets, 400 Northwest Coast Indian baskets.

00:31:12.159 --> 00:31:18.429
And I was down at the Pacific Galleries this
weekend looking around.

00:31:18.429 --> 00:31:27.239
I ended up buying four original posters of
the World's Fair from 1962.

00:31:27.239 --> 00:31:31.799
And Leslie asks me sometimes, "What makes
you collect?"

00:31:31.799 --> 00:31:32.799
I don't know.

00:31:32.799 --> 00:31:35.989
I can't explain what it is exactly that makes
me--.

00:31:35.989 --> 00:31:38.119
Some people like to collect.

00:31:38.119 --> 00:31:40.989
Other people, it's a bother.

00:31:40.989 --> 00:31:48.859
And the Collection Café was, we were gonna
have a café in the project no matter what.

00:31:48.859 --> 00:31:53.950
And it was just the perfect opportunity to
get rid of some of those collections.

00:31:53.950 --> 00:31:54.950
[laughter]

00:31:54.950 --> 00:31:59.440
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: So, I was there this morning
and you'll be able to see 28 of Dale's collections

00:31:59.440 --> 00:32:02.019
up close, including, actually, inside the
tables.

00:32:02.019 --> 00:32:07.399
So, each table will have its own collection
of some of the things that Dale has collected

00:32:07.399 --> 00:32:11.700
over the years, everything from miniature
dogs to bottle openers.

00:32:11.700 --> 00:32:13.469
There's antique radios.

00:32:13.469 --> 00:32:19.590
There's a lot of really interesting artifacts
that come with the café part of the museum.

00:32:19.590 --> 00:32:21.480
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: And that's been a lot of fun.

00:32:21.480 --> 00:32:23.840
We did a little--.

00:32:23.840 --> 00:32:24.859
I'll tell you what.

00:32:24.859 --> 00:32:26.610
We'll give everybody a little booklet.

00:32:26.610 --> 00:32:33.929
But you don't get them today, but I did a
