00:32:33.929 --> 00:32:35.970
each collection.

00:32:35.970 --> 00:32:42.669
And I printed 20 thousand of them to be given
away at the café.

00:32:42.669 --> 00:32:43.669
And Leslie, no.

00:32:43.669 --> 00:32:44.669
Yeah.

00:32:44.669 --> 00:32:45.669
Leslie just told me today--

00:32:45.669 --> 00:32:46.669
&gt;&gt;Leslie Chihuly: They're in.

00:32:46.669 --> 00:32:47.669
They're in.

00:32:47.669 --> 00:32:48.669
Big boxes full.

00:32:48.669 --> 00:32:49.669
All right.

00:32:49.669 --> 00:32:50.669
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: they came in.

00:32:50.669 --> 00:32:51.669
It costs 51 cents each to print.

00:32:51.669 --> 00:32:52.669
[Female Presenter laughs]

00:32:52.669 --> 00:32:54.749
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: And I've heard they've
been a hot commodity.

00:32:54.749 --> 00:32:57.999
There's been two proof books today that people
keep wanting to take with them.

00:32:57.999 --> 00:33:03.279
So, it'll be interesting to see them, the
final product.

00:33:03.279 --> 00:33:05.190
Your work really happens in series.

00:33:05.190 --> 00:33:09.429
And you have some series for which you're
very well-known--the Macchia, the Venetians,

00:33:09.429 --> 00:33:11.249
the Sea Forms.

00:33:11.249 --> 00:33:18.110
Do you have one series that you really love
revisiting, or one that you like the best?

00:33:18.110 --> 00:33:19.110
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: Oh.

00:33:19.110 --> 00:33:22.899
I've been asked that question before and I
don't really have a good answer.

00:33:22.899 --> 00:33:25.190
It changes, you know?

00:33:25.190 --> 00:33:30.529
Right now, I've been thinking about a series
that I started a few years ago called "The

00:33:30.529 --> 00:33:32.649
Jerusalem Cylinders."

00:33:32.649 --> 00:33:38.840
And in the next couple of weeks, we're gonna
start working on those again.

00:33:38.840 --> 00:33:42.460
So, I'm thinking about Jerusalem Cylinders.

00:33:42.460 --> 00:33:44.759
Right now, they're a favorite.

00:33:44.759 --> 00:33:48.010
But sometimes, it's the baskets.

00:33:48.010 --> 00:33:50.100
Sometimes, it's the Sea Forms.

00:33:50.100 --> 00:33:55.239
It really does change because they were all--.

00:33:55.239 --> 00:33:59.469
I thought about all of them before I ever
developed them into a series.

00:33:59.469 --> 00:34:01.039
I didn't just say, "OK.

00:34:01.039 --> 00:34:06.649
I'm gonna make baskets and then make, work
for two years on baskets."

00:34:06.649 --> 00:34:13.099
I waited until I really felt that I had something
concrete before I pursued it.

00:34:13.099 --> 00:34:15.409
So, it's hard to say.

00:34:15.409 --> 00:34:18.520
I wish I could answer that better for you.

00:34:18.520 --> 00:34:21.460
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: And in the exhibit hall,
there's eight rooms.

00:34:21.460 --> 00:34:23.579
And each of them map to one of the series.

00:34:23.579 --> 00:34:25.829
And they have different themes.

00:34:25.829 --> 00:34:33.510
One of the interesting pieces about the exhibit
is that it's in one of Seattle's highest traffic

00:34:33.510 --> 00:34:34.510
areas.

00:34:34.510 --> 00:34:35.510
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: Thank you.

00:34:35.510 --> 00:34:36.510
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Like, lots of people go
to the Space Needle.

00:34:36.510 --> 00:34:43.119
You've been really putting the Garden and
Glass together with the public watching.

00:34:43.119 --> 00:34:47.659
Have there been particular pieces in exhibits
that have been really hard to install?

00:34:47.659 --> 00:34:49.619
Are there any good stories of assembly so
far?

00:34:49.619 --> 00:34:51.740
&gt;&gt;Michelle Bufano: I don't know if we're allowed
to say those stories.

00:34:51.740 --> 00:34:52.740
[laughter]

00:34:52.740 --> 00:34:53.740
No.

00:34:53.740 --> 00:34:54.740
I think you're--

00:34:54.740 --> 00:34:55.740
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: I'll tell you.

00:34:55.740 --> 00:34:56.740
&gt;&gt;Michelle Bufano: looking at--

00:34:56.740 --> 00:34:57.740
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Yeah.

00:34:57.740 --> 00:34:58.740
&gt;&gt;Michelle Bufano: one of the most challenging
right there.

00:34:58.740 --> 00:35:00.920
&gt;&gt;Leslie Chihuly: That armature for the Glass
House was probably one of the most high-level

00:35:00.920 --> 00:35:02.200
engineering feats of all time.

00:35:02.200 --> 00:35:06.760
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: That makes me think of that
story I told you this at lunchtime about difficult

00:35:06.760 --> 00:35:13.510
situations, in that we blew glass in a little
village in France--Vion.

00:35:13.510 --> 00:35:15.539
And we made, I had the whole team over there.

00:35:15.539 --> 00:35:21.190
We had about 30 people working hand in hand
with the French glassblowers.

00:35:21.190 --> 00:35:29.390
And we made enough glass to fill two containers,
which we sent back to Seattle.

00:35:29.390 --> 00:35:32.490
Only one of the containers arrived.

00:35:32.490 --> 00:35:35.480
The other went over the side of the ship.

00:35:35.480 --> 00:35:40.630
And comes to find out that if you wanna ship
a container, if you want your container to

00:35:40.630 --> 00:35:44.089
be below deck, you have to pay an extra tariff.

00:35:44.089 --> 00:35:45.089
[laughter]

00:35:45.089 --> 00:35:50.549
And somewhere, that container has got a lot
of bubble wrap in it.

00:35:50.549 --> 00:35:53.250
So, I'll bet it's close to the surface somewhere.

00:35:53.250 --> 00:35:54.250
[laughter]

00:35:54.250 --> 00:35:56.000
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: We talked that those containers
often float.

00:35:56.000 --> 00:35:59.190
So, that's the hazard of doing work abroad.

00:35:59.190 --> 00:36:04.950
But that said, I do think your time at University
of Wisconsin and Venice, more specifically

00:36:04.950 --> 00:36:07.490
abroad, had really influenced your work.

00:36:07.490 --> 00:36:13.329
Can you give us a little bit of insight into
how each of those locations has shaped your

00:36:13.329 --> 00:36:14.849
work and your vision today?

00:36:14.849 --> 00:36:17.510
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: Well, let's see.

00:36:17.510 --> 00:36:23.880
At the University of Wisconsin, I was coming
with a degree in Interior Design and Architecture.

00:36:23.880 --> 00:36:30.180
I really hadn't made any art to say.

00:36:30.180 --> 00:36:36.470
And so when I got there, I was gonna be in
a graduate fine arts program.

00:36:36.470 --> 00:36:43.270
And I was really lucky to meet a couple of
guys that were far more talented than I was.

00:36:43.270 --> 00:36:46.010
And I ended up, one of them was a roommate.

00:36:46.010 --> 00:36:52.049
And during that year, I really learned a great
deal about art, not from my faculty, but from

00:36:52.049 --> 00:36:54.450
these guys I was living with.

00:36:54.450 --> 00:36:58.410
And that set me off in the right direction.

00:36:58.410 --> 00:36:59.410
And when I went to the--.

00:36:59.410 --> 00:37:00.410
What did you ask?

00:37:00.410 --> 00:37:01.410
The Rhode Island School of Design?

00:37:01.410 --> 00:37:03.559
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: That or Venice.

00:37:03.559 --> 00:37:05.880
Either one or both.

00:37:05.880 --> 00:37:07.970
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: Both.

00:37:07.970 --> 00:37:10.049
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Yeah.

00:37:10.049 --> 00:37:13.529
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: Well, either one.

00:37:13.529 --> 00:37:14.529
I'll take Venice.

00:37:14.529 --> 00:37:15.529
[laughter] Venice, I arrived in Venice.

00:37:15.529 --> 00:37:22.170
I had a Fulbright, which pays, I think it
paid 450 dollars a month at that time.

00:37:22.170 --> 00:37:28.069
And I arrived in Venice feeling a little depressed
from graduating.

00:37:28.069 --> 00:37:34.819
And I finally made my way out to the Venini
Glass Works, one of the most famous glass

00:37:34.819 --> 00:37:35.829
works.

00:37:35.829 --> 00:37:43.550
And I had a letter from them saying that I
could observe there for three weeks.

00:37:43.550 --> 00:37:50.170
And I met the owner and he had just gotten
a possibility of doing a commission--a large

00:37:50.170 --> 00:37:55.339
commission--in a town square of Ferrara.

00:37:55.339 --> 00:38:01.270
And they didn't have any experience or anybody
there that could really design something like

00:38:01.270 --> 00:38:02.270
that.

00:38:02.270 --> 00:38:04.540
And I talked him into letting me design it.

00:38:04.540 --> 00:38:06.980
And I used glass.

00:38:06.980 --> 00:38:08.150
I used plastic.

00:38:08.150 --> 00:38:10.880
I used neon.

00:38:10.880 --> 00:38:14.220
And so, I got set up.

00:38:14.220 --> 00:38:19.069
I was given my own studio up on top of the
factory.

00:38:19.069 --> 00:38:24.650
And there, I mean, I could have blown glass
there if I wanted to, but they were so much

00:38:24.650 --> 00:38:25.740
better than I was.

00:38:25.740 --> 00:38:27.710
It was too embarrassing.

00:38:27.710 --> 00:38:30.640
But I got to watch all the time.

00:38:30.640 --> 00:38:35.539
And that's really one of the best ways to
learn about glassblowing and a lot of other

00:38:35.539 --> 00:38:38.920
skills, crafts, is by watching.

00:38:38.920 --> 00:38:44.600
And I learned, 'cause back in the States,
everybody had been working by themselves.

00:38:44.600 --> 00:38:46.980
And glassblowing doesn't work very well by
yourself.

00:38:46.980 --> 00:38:50.529
It really takes a team of two or three.

00:38:50.529 --> 00:38:55.609
We work with a minimum of about eight people
on the team at any one time.

00:38:55.609 --> 00:39:01.049
And up as many as 15 people on a team, working
on the same piece of glass.

00:39:01.049 --> 00:39:05.619
So, what I learned more than anything, what
I learned from Venice was teamwork.

00:39:05.619 --> 00:39:10.050
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: And in addition, you're
best known for glassblowing, but you also

00:39:10.050 --> 00:39:11.150
paint and draw.

00:39:11.150 --> 00:39:13.779
And one of my favorite things about Dale,
I don't know if you guys can see his shoes,

00:39:13.779 --> 00:39:16.760
but he always has paint-smattered shoes.

00:39:16.760 --> 00:39:22.510
[laughs] So, tell us a little bit about how
drawing and painting influences your inspirations

00:39:22.510 --> 00:39:23.510
as an artist.

00:39:23.510 --> 00:39:24.829
And how is that part of your process?

00:39:24.829 --> 00:39:29.010
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: Well, I never really drew
that much.

00:39:29.010 --> 00:39:37.089
I mean, even though in undergraduate, I had
to make drawings of interiors and architecture.

00:39:37.089 --> 00:39:44.380
After that, I never drew that much, but I
lost the sight of my eye in 1976, which meant

00:39:44.380 --> 00:39:48.829
I had no peripheral vision and no depth perception.

00:39:48.829 --> 00:39:54.289
And that made it difficult to work out there
with a team because for obvious reasons.

00:39:54.289 --> 00:39:59.750
And so, from that point on, I started having
one of the really great glassblowers on the

00:39:59.750 --> 00:40:03.880
team, a young man named William Morris.

00:40:03.880 --> 00:40:11.910
I had Billy head up the team and I would make
drawings to show him what I wanted to make.

00:40:11.910 --> 00:40:16.250
And so, that was back in the late '70s.

00:40:16.250 --> 00:40:19.730
And I've been drawing and painting ever since.

00:40:19.730 --> 00:40:24.789
A lot of times it won't be necessarily about
what I'm gonna make.

00:40:24.789 --> 00:40:27.839
It'll just be, I just like to paint.

00:40:27.839 --> 00:40:34.099
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: I think one of the things
that had really, in addition to the scale

00:40:34.099 --> 00:40:38.829
of your work, that really sets your work apart
is the thinness of the glass--how thin you're

00:40:38.829 --> 00:40:41.609
able to blow it as well as the vibrancy of
the color.

00:40:41.609 --> 00:40:45.970
And I imagine that some of those things are
advances that you've developed with your team.

00:40:45.970 --> 00:40:49.670
Are there other technological advances that
have come along in the past 40 years that

00:40:49.670 --> 00:40:52.070
have really changed glassblowing?

00:40:52.070 --> 00:41:03.339
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: Probably the thin glass, working
that way, was definitely innovative, but that

00:41:03.339 --> 00:41:04.960
allowed us to--.

00:41:04.960 --> 00:41:10.020
When it was thin like that, we could heat
it up in the furnace and it would begin to

00:41:10.020 --> 00:41:12.119
collapse, or go asymmetrical.

00:41:12.119 --> 00:41:15.769
Glass, if you let it go on its own, it wants
to be symmetrical.

00:41:15.769 --> 00:41:24.900
So, if you're gonna make it like these pieces
here, are perfectly round and without having

00:41:24.900 --> 00:41:28.559
that scalloped edge, until the last reheat.

00:41:28.559 --> 00:41:32.190
Then, it's heated up and it's spun open.

00:41:32.190 --> 00:41:35.420
They're about two feet in diameter--a little
more.

00:41:35.420 --> 00:41:39.609
It's spun open and then it's spun harder.

00:41:39.609 --> 00:41:46.660
And the tips, because it had been blown in
what we call an optical mold, which is a ribbed

00:41:46.660 --> 00:41:51.980
mold, we blew it in there at a certain point,
which made the glass go thick and thin all

00:41:51.980 --> 00:41:53.250
the way around.

00:41:53.250 --> 00:41:56.460
And the thick parts remain hotter.

00:41:56.460 --> 00:41:59.690
And so, they come out and you get that scalloped
effect.

00:41:59.690 --> 00:42:13.290
And so, I suppose what I'm best known for
is asymmetrical glass using heat, fire, centrifugal

00:42:13.290 --> 00:42:16.420
force, gravity.

00:42:16.420 --> 00:42:19.029
Those are the tools.

00:42:19.029 --> 00:42:20.700
We use very few hand tools.

00:42:20.700 --> 00:42:24.750
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: And I think with that
question, what your answer is really about

00:42:24.750 --> 00:42:26.230
is about innovation.

00:42:26.230 --> 00:42:30.971
And so, one of the questions I'd like to ask
all three of you is, are there things that

00:42:30.971 --> 00:42:35.470
you've learned along the way through the partnerships,
through developing the exhibit, and also through

00:42:35.470 --> 00:42:40.130
your work, through the many schools--Pilchuck,
Rhode Island School of Design--are there lessons

00:42:40.130 --> 00:42:43.819
that you think could apply to tech and to
other industries, things you've learned along

00:42:43.819 --> 00:42:47.880
the way that you think are true about pushing
a science or a medium forward?

00:42:47.880 --> 00:42:50.510
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: Well, probably teamwork.

00:42:50.510 --> 00:42:51.510
[laughter]

00:42:51.510 --> 00:42:57.620
&gt;&gt;Leslie Chihuly: I'm just thinking about
the new model that this Chihuly Garden and

00:42:57.620 --> 00:43:02.110
Glass represents because it's really privately
owned and operated by the Wright family.

00:43:02.110 --> 00:43:05.170
And it's called Wright Art, LLC.

00:43:05.170 --> 00:43:09.740
And so, this is the first time that something
like this has been done in the city and yet,

00:43:09.740 --> 00:43:11.680
we're partnering with non-profit groups.

00:43:11.680 --> 00:43:12.680
We're not a non-profit.

00:43:12.680 --> 00:43:14.990
We're not building a non-profit board.

00:43:14.990 --> 00:43:15.990
We're not fund-raising.

00:43:15.990 --> 00:43:21.849
So, the fact that it's been in private investment
by a leading family in the community is new.

00:43:21.849 --> 00:43:26.950
And the fact that it's being done, in some
ways, to feel like a museum, to feel like

00:43:26.950 --> 00:43:30.970
a non-profit, and the kinds of programs and
commitment that we have to community.

00:43:30.970 --> 00:43:36.329
So, I think it's really a very innovative
approach to the organization.

00:43:36.329 --> 00:43:38.299
&gt;&gt;Michelle Bufano: That's great.

00:43:38.299 --> 00:43:47.279
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: You know, the most important
of all is being creative, which is, would

00:43:47.279 --> 00:43:53.039
be obviously critical to what you guys do.

00:43:53.039 --> 00:43:56.260
And obviously critical to what I do.

00:43:56.260 --> 00:44:04.109
And just being as innovative as you possibly
can.

00:44:04.109 --> 00:44:05.720
Get up early and have a lot of ideas.

00:44:05.720 --> 00:44:06.720
[laughter]

00:44:06.720 --> 00:44:11.030
&gt;&gt;Michelle Bufano: So, as I've been reading,
though, about Dale's work, and preparing,

00:44:11.030 --> 00:44:15.450
one thing is the way that you--you brought
it up earlier, Marissa--about he continues,

00:44:15.450 --> 00:44:20.240
you continue to go back to a series and push
it a little bit further.

00:44:20.240 --> 00:44:25.410
And the end result of that ends up being something
completely different maybe than you started

00:44:25.410 --> 00:44:27.640
with ten years ago or 20 years ago.

00:44:27.640 --> 00:44:34.160
And I think that is one thing that we could
all learn in our different disciplines that

00:44:34.160 --> 00:44:35.160
we work in.

00:44:35.160 --> 00:44:41.210
And it's that pushing it, but also coming
back to it, revisiting the idea again in a

00:44:41.210 --> 00:44:42.210
different light.

00:44:42.210 --> 00:44:49.780
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: I wonder if, I touched on
this a minute ago, but if I'm starting off

00:44:49.780 --> 00:44:56.950
a new series, let's just say it happens to
be these Persians.

00:44:56.950 --> 00:45:03.000
And I'll work and I'll experiment and we'll
make them over and over, try different things.

00:45:03.000 --> 00:45:10.029
Then, at a certain point, I have a month or
two worth of work.

00:45:10.029 --> 00:45:17.150
And all through that process, I'm trying to
decide whether or not this work should become

00:45:17.150 --> 00:45:23.920
a series for me, whether or not it's worth
investing the time and energy.

00:45:23.920 --> 00:45:31.610
On the other hand, if I keep investing time
and energy into something that's gonna be

00:45:31.610 --> 00:45:35.030
a loser, that's a big mistake.

00:45:35.030 --> 00:45:41.400
And I have to decide at what point I cut it
loose, or at what point I decide that I'm

00:45:41.400 --> 00:45:42.960
gonna exhibit it.

00:45:42.960 --> 00:45:47.579
Once I exhibit it, it gets locked in.

00:45:47.579 --> 00:45:52.440
And I would imagine that the same thing applies
to what you do to a certain degree.

00:45:52.440 --> 00:45:56.819
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: There's a lot of prototyping
and iteration in what we do.

00:45:56.819 --> 00:46:00.030
And then also figuring out when are we going
to take something and really scale it.

00:46:00.030 --> 00:46:01.030
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: Yeah.

00:46:01.030 --> 00:46:03.150
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: It's the equivalent of
it, probably the technological equivalent

00:46:03.150 --> 00:46:07.590
of having a series and when are we going to
just let an experiment go.

00:46:07.590 --> 00:46:11.950
So, I'm gonna ask one more question, and then
we'll go to the audience for a few audience

00:46:11.950 --> 00:46:14.160
questions, if you guys have some.

00:46:14.160 --> 00:46:17.769
And my question is about, I think that this
piece that we're seeing here on the screen,

00:46:17.769 --> 00:46:22.529
which is the Glass House and the new Garden
and Glass House, is really innovative and

00:46:22.529 --> 00:46:24.090
it really is pushing the bounds.

00:46:24.090 --> 00:46:25.090
And it is the centerpiece.

00:46:25.090 --> 00:46:31.440
It's a hundred feet long, 40 feet tall, 14
hundred pieces of glass.

00:46:31.440 --> 00:46:32.760
What was the inspiration here?

00:46:32.760 --> 00:46:36.480
You said you always wanted to do it, but what
was it inspired by?

00:46:36.480 --> 00:46:43.960
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: Well, I always wanted to do
a glass house, which makes me think of a chapel

00:46:43.960 --> 00:46:46.799
or a cathedral.

00:46:46.799 --> 00:46:54.350
And I just designed the Glass House along
with what was gonna be inside.

00:46:54.350 --> 00:47:02.460
And again, it was primarily to make something
that people hadn't seen before with the most

00:47:02.460 --> 00:47:10.069
gorgeous color that I could do with the right
amount of work in the Glass House so that

00:47:10.069 --> 00:47:13.890
it didn't get overpowered because I love the
structure as well.

00:47:13.890 --> 00:47:16.690
&gt;&gt;Leslie Chihuly: One of our own--.

00:47:16.690 --> 00:47:18.859
Well, you could talk about this, the armature
itself.

00:47:18.859 --> 00:47:22.279
The structure of that was built in our studio.

00:47:22.279 --> 00:47:27.950
And I think over all of the years of the projects
that Dale's worked on, that particular aspect

00:47:27.950 --> 00:47:31.849
has gotten more and more sophisticated--the
engineering that goes into having something

00:47:31.849 --> 00:47:37.150
that's a hundred feet long overhead, suspended
from glass is something that's really not

00:47:37.150 --> 00:47:38.150
been done.

00:47:38.150 --> 00:47:41.540
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: I think one of the things
that Googlers can really relate to is, in

00:47:41.540 --> 00:47:44.193
your work, there's a ton of engineering.

00:47:44.193 --> 00:47:45.193
There's a lot of math.

00:47:45.193 --> 00:47:46.193
There's a lot of geometry.

00:47:46.193 --> 00:47:47.880
There's a lot of thinking through what will
work.

00:47:47.880 --> 00:47:51.529
And so with that, I'd like to invite some
of the Googlers to ask questions.

00:47:51.529 --> 00:47:53.990
Do we have any questions from the audience?

00:47:53.990 --> 00:48:00.930
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: One thing is that--you're
probably familiar with this--but if the chandelier

00:48:00.930 --> 00:48:09.670
weighs, say, a thousand pounds--this one probably
weighs 25 thousand pounds--but if it weighed

00:48:09.670 --> 00:48:15.240
a thousand pounds, we're gonna put it in Google
someplace.

00:48:15.240 --> 00:48:19.269
The engineers wanna rate it to hold five thousand
pounds.

00:48:19.269 --> 00:48:27.349
So, it's a five to one ratio, which is, which
can be a problem 'cause somebody wants a chandelier

00:48:27.349 --> 00:48:33.140
in their house and it just won't support the,
what's required from engineering.

00:48:33.140 --> 00:48:37.740
It would support it, but not the way the engineers
wanna support it.

00:48:37.740 --> 00:48:42.529
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Well, I remember in some
of your Persian ceilings, I remember reading--I

00:48:42.529 --> 00:48:44.480
was surprised by that the glass actually has
flex.

00:48:44.480 --> 00:48:49.480
So, over these long expanses of glass that
other pieces of glass sit on, you actually,

00:48:49.480 --> 00:48:51.750
you need a five foot piece.

00:48:51.750 --> 00:48:55.900
You actually need five foot and a half an
inch because it actually will bow, which I

00:48:55.900 --> 00:49:00.539
didn't realize the glass actually had that
much play and flexibility in it.

00:49:00.539 --> 00:49:02.549
So, do we have a question?

00:49:02.549 --> 00:49:07.190
&gt;&gt;male #1: So, this is a beautiful exhibit.

00:49:07.190 --> 00:49:09.010
I have to know, what's next?

00:49:09.010 --> 00:49:11.579
What other exhibits do you have in the pipeline?

00:49:11.579 --> 00:49:12.579
[pause]

00:49:12.579 --> 00:49:15.359
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: Leslie, tell him what we're
doing.

00:49:15.359 --> 00:49:16.359
[laughter]

00:49:16.359 --> 00:49:20.059
&gt;&gt;Leslie Chihuly: Before we open this Chihuly
Garden and Glass, we've got a show at the

00:49:20.059 --> 00:49:22.630
Dallas Arboretum coming up first week of May.

00:49:22.630 --> 00:49:25.940
It'll be up through the summer, just during
tornado season.

00:49:25.940 --> 00:49:29.480
So, we'll see how we fare on that.

00:49:29.480 --> 00:49:32.359
And then in the fall, we've got Virginia Museum
of Fine Arts.

00:49:32.359 --> 00:49:37.329
Coming up another, less than a year after
that is the Montreal Museum of Fine Arts.

00:49:37.329 --> 00:49:42.589
And we're looking at some interesting projects
in Shanghai and in Beijing in terms of museum

00:49:42.589 --> 00:49:47.510
shows and interesting exhibition opportunities.

00:49:47.510 --> 00:49:48.510
[pause]

00:49:48.510 --> 00:49:49.830
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: Yeah.

00:49:49.830 --> 00:49:58.950
Dallas will be the, I think it's the 12th
Arboretum or Conservatory show that I've done,

00:49:58.950 --> 00:50:02.260
starting about ten years ago.

00:50:02.260 --> 00:50:09.119
And that was a great deal to do because of
my interest in glass and glasshouses and greenhouses.

00:50:09.119 --> 00:50:15.279
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: You've talked a lot about
mentorship and teamwork, both the way you

00:50:15.279 --> 00:50:20.890
were mentored early on by getting to watch
some of your fellow students and peers work.

00:50:20.890 --> 00:50:25.960
There's a really happening, burgeoning art
scene here in Seattle.

00:50:25.960 --> 00:50:31.810
How do you envision Chihuly Garden and Glass
and your studio interacting with that, with

00:50:31.810 --> 00:50:34.299
that group of artists?

00:50:34.299 --> 00:50:37.200
&gt;&gt;Leslie Chihuly: One factoid that we've mentioned
in the past, I don't know if you're aware,

00:50:37.200 --> 00:50:42.079
but it's that we actually have more people
working in glass in the Seattle area than

00:50:42.079 --> 00:50:44.690
in anywhere else in the world, including Morano.

00:50:44.690 --> 00:50:45.690
So, this is the--.

00:50:45.690 --> 00:50:49.349
And we've also got an MFA and a BA program
in glass now, the UW.

00:50:49.349 --> 00:50:52.230
We've got the Pilchuck Glass School, which
I mentioned earlier.

00:50:52.230 --> 00:50:59.240
So, there's a constant evolution of the educational
aspects that are possible for people in this

00:50:59.240 --> 00:51:00.579
area at all ages.

00:51:00.579 --> 00:51:05.309
We've got an at-risk glassblowing program
that's integrated into the Tacoma Public Schools,

00:51:05.309 --> 00:51:07.119
called the Hilltop Program.

00:51:07.119 --> 00:51:12.539
So, really at all ages, we're thinking about
glass and education around glass as an opportunity,

00:51:12.539 --> 00:51:16.890
sort of as a lift-off point for creative thinking,
for working with your hands, for thinking

00:51:16.890 --> 00:51:19.319
about ideas conceptually.

00:51:19.319 --> 00:51:20.980
And who knows?

00:51:20.980 --> 00:51:25.390
You think about the great history of glass
and what used to happen in Venice is that

00:51:25.390 --> 00:51:30.019
if you escaped the island of Venice and you
made it to England with the secrets, you were

00:51:30.019 --> 00:51:31.019
knighted.

00:51:31.019 --> 00:51:33.380
But if you were caught leaving Venice, you
were beheaded.

00:51:33.380 --> 00:51:39.730
So, Dale, one of his great innovations in
really generous gifts to the art community

00:51:39.730 --> 00:51:42.220
is that he really opened up the community.

00:51:42.220 --> 00:51:43.559
He opened up the secrets.

00:51:43.559 --> 00:51:46.730
He invited the great glass masters of Venice
to come and work here.

00:51:46.730 --> 00:51:51.460
And so now, there's this passing of the torch
that goes back and forth between the people

00:51:51.460 --> 00:51:55.339
who've worked in glass for a long time and
those who are coming into it now.

00:51:55.339 --> 00:51:57.210
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: We have a few questions
here at the microphone.

00:51:57.210 --> 00:52:00.800
&gt;&gt;female #1: So, something in the lines along
education.

00:52:00.800 --> 00:52:06.910
So, you mentioned that you started out with
glassblowing pretty little.

00:52:06.910 --> 00:52:08.789
How little were you?

00:52:08.789 --> 00:52:12.769
And how little will be a kid to be old enough
to do glassblowing?

00:52:12.769 --> 00:52:16.019
And do you have any advice for kids that are
too little?

00:52:16.019 --> 00:52:22.980
What can they do at home or to start having
the creativity explored in them?

00:52:22.980 --> 00:52:28.210
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: Well, our son started blowing
glass when he was about eight.

00:52:28.210 --> 00:52:33.039
Unfortunately, he quit when he was about ten.

00:52:33.039 --> 00:52:35.019
[laughter]

00:52:35.019 --> 00:52:41.190
But there are a couple of other kids that
blow glass at around eight or nine years old.

00:52:41.190 --> 00:52:43.569
You can get quite good, actually.

00:52:43.569 --> 00:52:50.430
Something they can do at a younger age is
to, it's what I did when I was in college

00:52:50.430 --> 00:52:52.070
getting my degree.

00:52:52.070 --> 00:52:55.630
And I started putting those bits of glass
in tapestries.

00:52:55.630 --> 00:52:59.160
I needed to make it so that the glass wasn't
sharp.

00:52:59.160 --> 00:53:04.480
So, I got a little oven, about two feet across,
that would go up to--.

00:53:04.480 --> 00:53:06.549
It was a ceramic oven.

00:53:06.549 --> 00:53:09.890
It went up to about 25 hundred degrees.

00:53:09.890 --> 00:53:16.339
And so, I would put them in the oven and take
it up high enough to round the edges.

00:53:16.339 --> 00:53:22.450
And then, I started putting one piece attached
to another, which is called fusing.

00:53:22.450 --> 00:53:27.040
And then, I started working with making little
three-dimensional sculptures.

00:53:27.040 --> 00:53:36.000
But you can have, I would imagine, you could
have probably from about the age of five,

00:53:36.000 --> 00:53:41.839
you could have kids start working with stained
glass, or glass fusing.

00:53:41.839 --> 00:53:47.059
Glass fusing would be easier, actually, than
stained glass.

00:53:47.059 --> 00:53:51.599
You have to figure out at point can they cut
the glass.

00:53:51.599 --> 00:53:55.029
Probably learn at a pretty young age.

00:53:55.029 --> 00:53:56.220
Was that your question?

00:53:56.220 --> 00:53:58.990
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: We'll take one more question.

00:53:58.990 --> 00:54:02.640
&gt;&gt;male #2: So, an exhibit like this probably
takes a lot of planning for light.

00:54:02.640 --> 00:54:07.630
And how did you do that for, how do you plan
to have the lighting effect this exhibit when

00:54:07.630 --> 00:54:09.130
it's not sunny in Seattle?

00:54:09.130 --> 00:54:10.130
[laughter]

00:54:10.130 --> 00:54:11.130
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: I couldn't hear.

00:54:11.130 --> 00:54:12.130
Could you hear it?

00:54:12.130 --> 00:54:16.170
&gt;&gt;Leslie Chihuly: He's talking about light
and how did we plan it with the effect of

00:54:16.170 --> 00:54:17.170
light, and--.

00:54:17.170 --> 00:54:18.170
&gt;&gt;male #2: Yeah.

00:54:18.170 --> 00:54:20.670
Like, you need a lot of light for something
like this to, with glass, right?

00:54:20.670 --> 00:54:21.670
And--.

00:54:21.670 --> 00:54:22.670
&gt;&gt;Michelle Bufano: I can tell you this.

00:54:22.670 --> 00:54:26.700
At different times of the day, you have a
completely different experience in the Glass

00:54:26.700 --> 00:54:32.650
House and the way that the light of the day
reflects on the glass that's in there.

00:54:32.650 --> 00:54:39.359
What's so amazing about it is that it actually
changes as there's sun or no light.

00:54:39.359 --> 00:54:43.289
It's just amazing to look at the different
qualities of the glass.

00:54:43.289 --> 00:54:46.980
And I think that's one of the reasons people
will continue to keep coming back is just

00:54:46.980 --> 00:54:48.789
to see that difference.

00:54:48.789 --> 00:54:51.160
But as far as the planning goes, that was
all Dale's vision.

00:54:51.160 --> 00:54:52.160
[laughs]

00:54:52.160 --> 00:54:56.859
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: You know, there are really
only three or four materials that transmit

00:54:56.859 --> 00:54:59.009
light of any scale.

00:54:59.009 --> 00:55:07.700
There are a few gems, like diamonds and things,
but materials of any scale there's only glass,

00:55:07.700 --> 00:55:08.700
plastic--.

00:55:08.700 --> 00:55:11.710
Actually, this is a good audience.

00:55:11.710 --> 00:55:13.700
See if I'm wrong.

00:55:13.700 --> 00:55:14.700
[laughter]

00:55:14.700 --> 00:55:21.200
You got glass, plastic, ice, and water.

00:55:21.200 --> 00:55:22.200
Those are--.

00:55:22.200 --> 00:55:24.480
Alabaster would be one maybe.

00:55:24.480 --> 00:55:29.150
Those are about the only material that light
can go through.

00:55:29.150 --> 00:55:33.740
And that's what makes glass so incredibly
mysterious.

00:55:33.740 --> 00:55:36.009
If you have a little bit of--.

00:55:36.009 --> 00:55:41.420
If I put a piece of red glass on the wall
down there, a hundred feet down the other

00:55:41.420 --> 00:55:52.030
end, one inch square, and I lit it from behind
with the sun or with a Par 36 light bulb,

00:55:52.030 --> 00:55:54.790
you would easily see that one inch square.

00:55:54.790 --> 00:55:57.790
Any other material, you couldn't even see
it.

00:55:57.790 --> 00:56:00.540
There's something very magical about glass.

00:56:00.540 --> 00:56:03.109
Did anybody think of another material?

00:56:03.109 --> 00:56:04.109
See?

00:56:04.109 --> 00:56:05.550
It's tough.

00:56:05.550 --> 00:56:06.550
[laughter]

00:56:06.550 --> 00:56:11.289
&gt;&gt;Female Presenter: Well, and actually going
through the exhibit today, I think that it

00:56:11.289 --> 00:56:12.799
actually merits a few visits.

00:56:12.799 --> 00:56:17.400
Like, I started noticing that at first, you
notice all the color and the shapes and the

00:56:17.400 --> 00:56:18.400
forms.

00:56:18.400 --> 00:56:22.279
And then, you start to realize how many different
lights there are here and there--the actual

00:56:22.279 --> 00:56:26.359
engineering behind the exhibit, and the armatures
and things like that.

00:56:26.359 --> 00:56:30.650
And so, I definitely encourage all of you
to go to Chihuly Garden and Glass when it

00:56:30.650 --> 00:56:31.650
opens on May 23rd?

00:56:31.650 --> 00:56:32.650
May 21st.

00:56:32.650 --> 00:56:36.271
So, definitely encourage you to go visit,
make multiple visits.

00:56:36.271 --> 00:56:37.420
There's a lot there to see.

00:56:37.420 --> 00:56:41.569
It's like a combination of bringing together
an amazing career and a career that's still

00:56:41.569 --> 00:56:45.499
in progress that I'm sure we're gonna see
even more great things from in the future.

00:56:45.499 --> 00:56:49.390
And it's been a huge honor to have all of
you here today to talk about the project and

00:56:49.390 --> 00:56:51.640
talk about your career and your accomplishments.

00:56:51.640 --> 00:56:52.670
&gt;&gt;Dale Chihuly: It's our honor.

00:56:52.670 --> 00:56:53.670
Thank you so much.

00:56:53.670 --> 00:56:54.670
&gt;&gt;Leslie Chihuly: Thank you.

00:56:54.670 --> 00:56:55.670
&gt;&gt;Michelle Bufano: Thank you.

00:56:55.670 --> 00:56:55.671
[applause]

